{
  "text": "Hoffman et al. [CITATION_1] suggested that low preoperative testosterone was a predictive factor for high Gleason scores, and Schatzl et al. [CITATION_2] reported high associations between low preoperative testosterone and high Gleason scores. However, Massengill et al. [CITATION_3] examined 879 patients who underwent a radical prostatectomy and reported that low preoperative testosterone values were not associated with Gleason scores. The results of the present study also showed no correlation between preoperative testosterone values and Gleason scores.",
